  "Yes, a single counterexample disproves a universal statement": "",
  "No, she must check all 2x2 matrices": "",
  "No, only 3x3 counterexamples are valid": "",
  "A universal statement 'for all A, B: AB = BA' is disproved by a single counterexample. AB = [[1,1],[0,0]] but BA = [[0,0],[1,1]], so AB != BA. One counterexample suffices to disprove the claim.": "",
  "A student must prove that the determinant of an orthogonal matrix Q is +1 or -1. She writes: 'Q^T Q = I, so det(Q^T Q) = det(I) = 1.' What is the key algebraic step to conclude?": "",
  "det(Q^T Q) = det(Q^T) * det(Q) = det(Q)^2 = 1, so det(Q) = +1 or -1": "",
  "det(Q) = trace(Q)": "",
  "det(Q) = 1 because Q is invertible": "",
  "det(Q^T) = -det(Q)": "",
  "Using det(AB) = det(A)*det(B) and det(Q^T) = det(Q): det(Q^T Q) = det(Q^T)*det(Q) = det(Q)^2. Since det(Q^T Q) = det(I) = 1, we get det(Q)^2 = 1, so det(Q) = +/-1.": "",
  "To prove that the column space of A and the null space of A^T are orthogonal complements in R^m, a key step is showing that if y is in null(A^T) and x is in col(A), then:": "",
  "y = Ax, particularly regarding some in": "",
  "y^T x = y^T(Az) = (A^T y)^T z = 0^T z = 0 for some z": "",
  "det(A) = 0, particularly regarding then": "",
  "A is invertible, particularly regarding": "",
  "If x = Az for some z (x is in col(A)) and A^T y = 0 (y is in null(A^T)), then x . y = (Az)^T y = z^T A^T y = z^T 0 = 0. Every vector in col(A) is orthogonal to every vector in null(A^T).": "",
  "A student proves that trace(AB) = trace(BA) by manipulating the double sum. She writes: trace(AB) = sum_i (AB)_{ii} = sum_i sum_j A_{ij}B_{ji}. What does she do next?": "",
  "Apply the Cayley-Hamilton theorem": "",
  "Switch the order of summation: sum_j sum_i B_{ji}A_{ij} = sum_j (BA)_{jj} = trace(BA)": "",
  "Factor out the determinant": "",
  "Use the fact that A and B commute": "",
  "The double sum sum_i sum_j A_ij * B_ji can be reindexed: swap the summation order and relabel to get sum_j sum_i B_ji * A_ij = sum_j (BA)_jj = trace(BA). This elegant proof works for any matrices where the products are defined.": "",
  "A theorem states: 'A square matrix A is invertible if and only if det(A) != 0.' To prove the forward direction (A invertible => det(A) != 0), a student writes: 'If A is invertible, then AA^{-1} = I, so det(A)*det(A^{-1}) = det(I) = 1.' What does this imply?": "",
  "A must be symmetric, particularly regarding since": "",
  "det(A) cannot be zero, because otherwise 0 * det(A^{-1}) = 0 != 1": "",
  "det(A) = 1 always, particularly regarding moreover": "",
  "det(A^{-1}) = 0, particularly regarding prove as": "",
  "Since det(A) * det(A^{-1}) = 1, if det(A) were 0, then 0 * det(A^{-1}) = 0 != 1, a contradiction. Therefore det(A) != 0. Moreover, det(A^{-1}) = 1/det(A).": "",
  "A student must prove that the intersection of two subspaces is also a subspace. After showing the zero vector is in both, she needs to prove closure under addition. If u and v are in W1 intersection W2, why is u + v in both W1 and W2?": "",
  "Because the intersection contains all vectors from both subspaces": "",
  "u, v are in W1 (which is a subspace, so u+v is in W1), and u, v are in W2 (which is a subspace, so u+v is in W2)": "",
  "Because W1 and W2 have the same dimension": "",
  "Because u + v = v + u by commutativity": "",
  "Since u and v are in W1 (and W1 is a subspace, hence closed under addition), u + v is in W1. Similarly, since u and v are in W2, u + v is in W2. Therefore u + v is in W1 intersect W2.": "",
  "A proof of the spectral theorem for real symmetric matrices requires showing eigenvectors for different eigenvalues are orthogonal. Given Av1 = lambda1*v1 and Av2 = lambda2*v2 with A = A^T and lambda1 != lambda2, the key computation is:": "",
  "trace(A) = lambda1 + lambda2, particularly regarding since under equilibrium conditions": "",
  "lambda1*(v1 . v2) = (Av1)^T v2 = v1^T A^T v2 = v1^T Av2 = lambda2*(v1 . v2), so (lambda1 - lambda2)*(v1 . v2) = 0": "",
  "det(A) = lambda1 * lambda2, particularly regarding have in the context of this analysis": "",
  "v1 + v2 = 0, particularly regarding eigenvalues within the typical range of values": "",
  "lambda1*(v1.v2) = (Av1)^T v2 = v1^T(A^T)v2 = v1^T(Av2) = lambda2*(v1.v2). So (lambda1 - lambda2)(v1.v2) = 0. Since lambda1 != lambda2, we must have v1.v2 = 0, proving orthogonality.": "",
  "A student wants to prove that if A is nilpotent (A^k = 0 for some k), then all eigenvalues of A are 0. Which proof technique is most efficient?": "",
  "Proof by counterexample, particularly regarding whose as typically measured in practice": "",
